    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters May 1st with a lineup heavily incentivized by stolen base upside and platoon advantages. **Corbin Carroll** (76.43) leads the charge today against Rea; despite a marginal tax for facing an elite hold catcher, **Carroll** remains our premier start given his ability to manufacture runs in a favorable park environment. **Austin Riley** (74.61) is our strongest non-speed play, buoyed significantly by a high-ceiling matchup against Quintana. The 19% SP skill bonus is the primary driver here, as **Riley** is primed to capitalize on a soft matchup that elevates him well above his base projection. Meanwhile, **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) continues to be an undervalued asset, benefiting from a potent combination of a 14% park boost and a high-order assignment (#2) that maximizes his opportunities to produce against Holmes.\n\nOur focus on speed remains aggressive, with **Brice Turang** (70.52) locked into the utility slot. While the opposing catcher\u2019s pop time forces a slight efficiency haircut, the favorable matchup against Irvin and the high-order stability make him a core piece of our daily output. Conversely, **Jose Caballero** (65.81) provides a massive 13% platoon boost that easily clears the starting threshold. The most difficult decision rested on **Josh Naylor** (43.53), who sat on the cusp of the lineup; however, a difficult assignment against the stingy Ragans cratered his SP skill score, rendering him a bench option behind the higher-upside profiles of **Gabriel Moreno** and **Vinnie Pasquantino**.\n\nRisks for this slate are primarily found in the lower-tier starts. **James Wood** (54.46) carries significant volatility due to a tough draw against Misiorowski, though his leadoff spot and xwOBA profile keep him just above the bench floor. Similarly, **Tyler Soderstrom** (55.41) faces a tough path against Cantillo, and we are monitoring these spots closely to preserve our weekly game cap if the early innings signal a stagnant offensive performance. With **Giancarlo Stanton** and **Max Muncy** still sidelined on the IL, we are leaning heavily on the depth of players like **Cole Young**\u2014who fell just short of our 40-point efficiency floor today\u2014to keep our roster flexibility intact as we navigate these mid-week series.",
